{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
Following petitioner\rquote s application under s 204 of the Federal Power Act to respondent Federal Power Commission (FPC) for authorization of a bond issue, two intervening cities opposed the authorization on the ground that the proceeds of the bond issue would be used to finance or refinance certain anticompetitive activities in violation of the antitrust laws, the Federal Power Act, and the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 1935. Section 204(a) empowers the FPC to authorize a security issue only if the issue is found to be for some lawful purpose and compatible with the public interest. The FPC granted the cities\rquote  petition to intervene, denied their request for a hearing, and authorized the bond issue, holding that the cities\rquote  allegations were irrelevant to a requested authorization of securities under s 204. The Court of Appeals remanded the case for consideration of the cities\rquote  claim, holding that, in line with the reasoning in 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=1967129536&pubNum=708&originatingDoc=Iab938b559bf011d991d0cc6b54f12d4d&refType=RP&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.Search)" }{\fldrslt 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf5 \i0 
Denver s R.G.W.R. Co. v. United States, 387 U.S. 485, 87 S.Ct. 1754, 18 L.Ed.2d 905,
}}}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
 the FPC should have considered the alleged competitive consequences of the bond issue in the s 204 proceeding. Held:
\par 
}
}
}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
1. The FPC, as a general rule, must consider the anticompetitive consequences of a security issue under s 204. Pp. 1876\u8212\'3f1879.
\par 
}
}
}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
(a) The Federal Power Act did not render antitrust policy irrelevant to the FPC\rquote s regulation of the electric power industry. Pp. 1877\u8212\'3f1878.
\par 
}
}
}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
(b) The fact that the FPC has broad authority under other provisions of the Act to determine whether a public utility\rquote s conduct is in the public interest does not mean that the same standard is not equally germane under s 204. P. 1878.
\par 
}
}
}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
(c) Consideration of antitrust policies in the context of s 204 provides a first line of defense against anticompetitive practices that might later become the subject of an antitrust proceeding. Pp. 1878\u8212\'3f1879.
\par 
}
}
}
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\li0 \f2 \qj \b0 \ri0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
{\f2 \strike0 \ul0 \b0 \sa0 \sb0 \fs20 \cf1 \i0 
(d) The FPC, like the Interstate Commerce Commission, has broad regulatory authority, which includes responsibility for considering 
}
